  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Rochedale sits in Brisbane's southeastern corridor, bordered by Mackenzie, Mansfield, Eight Mile Plains and Rochedale South. It has been one of the most rapidly transformed suburbs in Brisbane over the past fifteen years, with masterplanned estates progressively delivering modern family homes that have changed both the look and the buyer profile of the area. The southern and central pockets are now defined by modern brick-and-render homes on level blocks, while the older eastern half retains the larger acreage and semi-rural blocks that defined Rochedale for decades. That internal contrast matters for sellers because the two halves of the suburb attract different buyer segments and need different campaign positioning.</p>

      <p>The Rochedale State School and Rochedale State High catchments are the gravitational centre of family demand in this suburb. The committed buyer who has chosen Rochedale over Mansfield, Wishart or Eight Mile Plains has often made that choice on the basis of the school catchment, and that decision is one they have usually researched carefully. A campaign that confirms catchment clearly from day one removes a friction point that otherwise sits between the buyer and an offer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Rochedale</h2>
      <p>The dominant buyer in modern Rochedale is the upgrader family from across south Brisbane, the inner south and the southeastern corridor. These buyers have outgrown their first home, are in their late thirties or forties, and have made a deliberate decision to commit to the Rochedale catchment for their children's primary and secondary schooling. They have visited enough open homes to know the standard, and they arrive ready to act when a property in the right catchment, at the right price, appears.</p>

      <p>The second consistent buyer group is the interstate family relocating from Sydney or Melbourne. Rochedale offers a value proposition that compares favourably with comparable southern Sydney or eastern Melbourne suburbs, and the masterplanned estate streetscapes read familiarly to buyers from those markets. These buyers often have a defined timeline tied to a job relocation or school enrolment date and tend to act decisively when their search converges on a suburb that meets their requirements.</p>

      <p>The acreage pocket in the eastern half of Rochedale attracts a different buyer entirely: the established household looking for a larger holding within the Brisbane city limits, often with equestrian or hobby-farm interests, and with the capacity to commit to a property that requires more land-management attention than a standard residential block. This buyer pool is smaller but more focused, and a campaign for an acreage property in Rochedale needs to reach into that buyer pool specifically rather than treat the listing as a generic residential property with extra land.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Rochedale</h2>
      <p>School catchment is a meaningful value driver. Properties that fall clearly within the Rochedale State School and Rochedale State High catchments command stronger buyer competition than comparable homes that sit on the wrong side of the catchment boundary. Sellers who can confirm and document the catchment for their address from the first day of campaign are positioning the property in front of the most committed family buyer pool.</p>

      <p>Estate quality and street position within the masterplanned areas matters more than buyers from outside Rochedale realise. Within the modern estates, there is an internal hierarchy: streets with established landscaping, quieter through-traffic, and proximity to the central parkland systems command a premium over otherwise comparable streets further from those amenities. A property's exact position within the estate is part of the value proposition, and the campaign should reflect that positioning rather than treat all modern Rochedale homes as interchangeable.</p>

      <p>Build quality and finish are factors that family buyers in modern Rochedale assess closely. They have visited enough comparable estates across south Brisbane to know what good build quality looks like, and properties that present with quality finishes, well-maintained outdoor entertaining areas, and considered landscaping outperform comparable homes that have been left in builder-standard condition.</p>

      <p>For the acreage pocket, land size, soil quality and zoning are the primary value drivers, with the home itself a secondary consideration for many buyers in that segment. The campaign for an acreage Rochedale property is fundamentally about the land, and the marketing should lead with that.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Rochedale home for sale</h2>
      <p>For the modern estate home, the preparation standard is high. Family buyers comparing the southern corridor will have visited multiple immaculately-presented homes across Mackenzie, Mansfield, Wishart and Rochedale itself, and the standard they expect is set by the best of those campaigns. Practical condition items, including small maintenance issues, dated paintwork, and tired landscaping, will form the basis of buyer discount negotiations if they are not addressed before the campaign starts. The investment in pre-sale preparation almost always returns multiples of its cost in the auction or offer environment.</p>

      <p>The outdoor entertaining area deserves particular attention. Modern Rochedale buyers expect a functional outdoor space, and a well-presented patio or alfresco area is one of the standard features that converts buyer interest into offer-ready intent. Sellers who present that space as polished, usable and aspirational are speaking directly to one of the dominant criteria in the family buyer decision.</p>

      <p>For the acreage pocket, presentation is about the land as much as the home. Fence lines, paddock condition, water infrastructure, and the general state of the holding all factor into the buyer's assessment. A pre-sale audit that addresses obvious deferred maintenance on the land side of the property will materially improve the campaign result.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Rochedale</h2>
      <p>Rochedale follows the broader Brisbane seasonal pattern, with autumn (late February through May) and spring (September through November) as the strongest windows for family property campaigns. Autumn tends to produce particularly motivated buyer conditions in the southern corridor because families who have been researching schools and comparing suburbs through summer arrive in February and March with clear intent and a timeline driven by the school year or a genuine life-stage change.</p>

      <p>Spring brings more buyers to the market but also more competing listings, and the autumn window's lower competing stock profile often gives a well-prepared Rochedale home a cleaner run against fewer alternatives. For acreage properties, the seasonal effect is less pronounced because the buyer pool is smaller and more event-driven, but campaigns that launch outside the broader Christmas and Easter quiet windows tend to perform more consistently.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Rochedale</h2>
      <p>Well-presented modern Rochedale homes, accurately priced against the most recent comparable sales for the specific estate and catchment, typically sell within 25 to 40 days. The family buyer who has been comparing the southeastern corridor will act decisively when a property in the right catchment at a price that reflects the genuine market appears. Acreage properties in the eastern pocket sit on the market longer, typically 35 to 60 days, because the buyer pool is smaller and the campaign needs more time to reach the right households.</p>

      <p>In both cases, correct pricing against current comparables is the most controllable factor in campaign duration. Overpriced campaigns sit longer than they should, attract offers that reflect the extended days on market, and almost always close at a discount that reflects the price-setting error rather than the market.</p>

